Think through the problem of SLO design for services with highly variable and inherently non-uniform workloads — specifically services where the natural performance distribution is multimodal, making a single SLO target inappropriate.

Consider a query API where some queries hit an in-memory cache (P99 = 10ms) and others require a full database scan (P99 = 3,000ms). A single P99 SLO at the service level will always be dominated by the database scan population. Setting P99 < 3,500ms protects against regressions in the slow path but says nothing about the cache path. Setting P99 < 100ms makes the SLO permanently infeasible because of the scan population.

One approach is to split into separate SLOs by query type. But this requires that query type is a well-defined, observable attribute. Think through: what happens when the split between fast and slow queries is not a clean categorical distinction but rather a continuous distribution of query complexity? How do you segment a continuous workload distribution into meaningful SLO populations without overfitting to current traffic patterns?

Another approach is to use Apdex per endpoint rather than a latency percentile SLO. Think through whether per-endpoint Apdex with individually calibrated T values actually solves the multimodal distribution problem, or whether it just moves the threshold calibration problem to a different level.

A third approach: define the SLO in terms of the fraction of users experiencing acceptable performance rather than the fraction of requests. A user making 10 requests of which 1 is slow may have a worse experience than the 90% request success rate suggests. Think through user-centric versus request-centric SLIs and when the distinction matters operationally.

Propose the SLO design approach you believe is most practical for a multimodal workload, justify your reasoning, and specify what monitoring instrumentation would be required to measure it.
